Let A'B'C' be the cevian triangle of a point P, and let A", B", C" be
the respective intersections of lines PA, PB, PC with the circumcircle
of triangle ABC. Let
<p>U = B'C"&cap;B"C'&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; V =
C'A"&cap;C"A'&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; W =
A'B"&cap;A"B'.</p>

<p>Lines AU, BV, CW concur in the 1st Saragossa point of P;<br>
lines A'U, B'V, C'W concur in the 2nd Saragossa point of P;<br>
lines A"U, B"V, C"W concur in the 3rd Saragossa point of P.</p>

<p>These concurrences were presented by Darij Grinberg (Hyacinthos
#6531, February 14, 2003),<br>
with coordinates as follows. Let P = x : y : z (trilinears), and
abbreviate the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd Saragossa points<br>
as Q, Q', Q", respectively; then first trilinears are</p>

<p>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;for
Q:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;f(a,b,c) = a/[x(bz + cy)],<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;for
Q':&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;f(a,b,c) =
ax[(b<sup>2</sup>z<sup>2</sup> + c<sup>2</sup>y<sup>2</sup>)x + xyzbc +
ayz(bz + cy)],<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;for
Q":&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;f(a,b,c) = ax[(b<sup>2</sup>z<sup>2</sup> +
c<sup>2</sup>y<sup>2</sup>)x + ayz(bz + cy)].
</p>
<p>
The name <i>Saragossa</i> refers to the king who proved Ceva's
theorem before Ceva did. See
</p>
<p><b>J. B. Hogendijk,</b> "Al-Mu'taman ibn Hud [bar over u], 11th
century king of Saragossa and brilliant mathematician," <i>Historia
Mathematica,</i> 22 (1995) 1-18.</p>

<p>The points P, Q', Q" are collinear.</p>

